Sure, I can help you with that. Here is a possible HTML/JS code that can turn the mock-up into a colorful website, where the jokes are replaced by two real jokes from ¹:

```html
<html>
<head>
  <style>
    body {
      background-color: lightblue;
      font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    }
    h1 {
      color: white;
      text-align: center;
    }
    .joke {
      margin: 20px;
      padding: 10px;
      border: 5px solid green;
      border-radius: 10px;
    }
    .joke h2 {
      color: green;
    }
    .joke p {
      color: black;
      display: none;
    }
    .joke button {
      background-color: green;
      color: white;
      border: none;
      padding: 10px;
      cursor: pointer;
    }
    .joke button:hover {
      opacity: 0.8;
    }
    footer {
      text-align: center;
      color: white;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>My Joke Website</h1>
  <div class="joke">
    <h2>Really funny joke 1</h2>
    <p>What do you call a fish wearing a bowtie? Sofishticated.</p>
    <button onclick="showPunchline(this)">Ersh to reveal punchline</button>
  </div>
  <div class="joke">
    <h2>Same, but joke 2</h2>
    <p>How does a penguin build its house? Igloos it together.</p>
    <button onclick="showPunchline(this)">Ersh to reveal punchline</button>
  </div>
  <footer>&copy; OpenAI 2023</footer>
  <script>
    function showPunchline(button) {
      // get the parent element of the button, which is the joke div
      var joke = button.parentElement;
      // get the first paragraph element inside the joke div, which is the punchline
      var punchline = joke.getElementsByTagName("p")[0];
      // toggle the display of the punchline
      if (punchline.style.display == "none") {
        punchline.style.display = "block";
        button.innerHTML = "Ersh to hide punchline";
      } else {
        punchline.style.display = "none";
        button.innerHTML = "Ersh to reveal punchline";
      }
    }
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

